\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
\begin_inset VSpace 135bp
\end_inset

Forecasting quity risk premium: is the predictive ability of technical indicator
s persistent?
\begin_inset VSpace 135bp
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Krisztián Szemán
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
2019
\begin_inset Newpage newpage
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Forecasting stock returns is an extremely difficult task that has been examined
 by numerous papers in the 21st century.
 Most of these studies focus on fundamental macroeconomic variables, and
 their ability to predict the excess return over the risk-free rate (equity
 risk premium) of a stock index.
 As Goyal and Welch 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Welch2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 shows, some fundamental variables such as the treasury bill rate or dividend
 yields can explain in-sample future stock returns to an extent, but their
 out-of-sample performances are inferior to that of the historical average
 forecast, which is generally considered a stringent benchmark.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Neely
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Neely2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 compares the performance of technical indicators and fundamental variables
 based on their ability to forecast the risk premium, and finds that technical
 indicators are predict more effectively during recessions, while models
 based on fundamental variables perform better during economic expansions.
 This implies that the predictive ability of a model based on a variable
 of either type is persistent over time, so assuming it performed well in
 the recent past, it is more likely do so in the current period.
 This phenomenon is called momentum of predictability (MoP) by Wang
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Wang2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A MoP based strategy switches between the forecast of the model of interest
 and the historical average forecast based on the performance of the two
 separate models in the past 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 months.
 Wang shows that there is significant relationship between past and current
 forecasting ability for certain fundamental variables, such as the dividend-pri
ce ratio, the treasury bill rate of the long-term yield, which leads to
 improved out-of-sample predicitive ability of individuals models using
 MoP-based time varying forecasts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This paper examines a naturally arising issue: is there an analogous, similarly
 valuable momentum of predictability for technical indicators? Using data
 from January 1950 to December 2017, and a total of 14 variables (6 moving
 average-based, 2 momentum-based, and 6 volume-based rules), I perform a
 test of momentum predictability in the same framework as Wang
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Wang2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, and find that there is no significant dependence between past and current
 predictability for the indicators.
 Even though out of the 70 computed p-values, 7 are lower than 5%, employing
 a False Discovery Rate (developed by Benjamini and Hochberg) test yields
 that none of the findings can actually be considered true positives.
 (In contrast, Wang finds p-value lower than 1% for five different variables
 on multiple lookback periods.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, I also compute the monthly average signal for a higher number
 of moving average-based (354 different strategies, following Okunev's paper),
 momentum-based (36), and volume-based (354) rules.
 The three average signals, and a principal component extracted from the
 744 variables taken together are also tested for momentum of predictability.
 The results are similar to the preceding section: the variables do not
 exhibit significant momentum of predictability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data and descriptive statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section describes the variables that are used to carry out the analysis.
 For the equity risk premium, the log of the value-weighted equity return
 including dividends minus the log of the lagged risk-free rate is used
 (available on Amit Goyal's homepage).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 14 technical indicators that are used are the same that Neely
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Neely2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 uses, and the methodology of computing the technical indicators can also
 be found in that paper.
 Nevertheless, it is included in this section for the sake of easier understandi
ng.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Out of the 14 variables, the first 6 are moving-average based rules, which
 generate a buy or sell signal (
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i,t}=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i,t}=0$
\end_inset

) at the end of period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 by comparing two moving averages:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i,t}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mathrm{\begin{array}{cc}
if & MA_{\mathit{s,t}}\geq MA_{\mathit{l,t}}\end{array}}\\
0 & \begin{array}{cc}
\mathrm{if} & \mathrm{MA}_{s,t}<\mathrm{MA}_{l,t},\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{MA_{\mathit{j,t}}=\left(\frac{1}{j}\right)}\stackrel[i=0]{j-1}{\sum}\mathrm{\mathit{P_{t-i}}},
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the level of the stock index, 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 are the lengths of the short and long MA (
\begin_inset Formula $s<l$
\end_inset

).
 I analyze monthly MA rules with 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l=9,12$
\end_inset

, and denote the indicators with MA lengths 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

 by MA(
\begin_inset Formula $s,l$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, 2 momentum based strategies are calculated.
 A momentum rule strategy guves a buy signal if the current stock price
 is higher than its level 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 periods ago:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i,t}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mathrm{\begin{array}{cc}
if & P_{\mathit{t}}\geq P_{\mathit{t-m}}\end{array}}\\
0 & \begin{array}{cc}
\mathrm{if} & \mathrm{P}_{t}<\mathrm{P}_{t-m.}\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

I employ monthly signals for 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 = 9,12 and denote them MOM(
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thirdly, 6 volume based strategies are considered, whicTherefore,h utilize
 trading volume as well as past price changes to identify market trends.
 Initially, the on-balance volume is defined as follows:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{OBV_{\mathit{t}}=\stackrel[k=1]{t}{\sum}VOL_{\mathit{k}}D_{\mathit{k}}},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{VOL}{}_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the trading volume during period 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{k}$
\end_inset

 is a binary variable which takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{k}\geq P_{k-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 From the values of
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{OBV}_{t}$
\end_inset

, the trading signal is computed in the following way:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S_{i,t}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mathrm{\begin{array}{cc}
if & MA_{\mathit{s,t}}^{OBV}\geq MA_{\mathit{l,t}}^{OBV}\end{array}}\\
0 & \begin{array}{cc}
\mathrm{if} & \mathrm{MA_{\mathit{s,t}}^{OBV}<MA_{\mathit{l,t}}^{OBV}},\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{MA_{\mathit{j,t}}^{OBV}=\left(\frac{1}{j}\right)}\stackrel[i=0]{j-1}{\sum}\mathrm{\mathit{\mathrm{OBV}_{t-i}}}.
\]

\end_inset

I calculate montly volume-based rules for 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,2,3$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l=9,12$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The market data of the S&P500 stock index is used from January 1950 to December
 2017.
 Due to the lack of earlier data for trading volume, we have observations
 for all technical indicators starting from only December 1950.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that due to the long-term upward trend in the index
 level, technical indicators more often generate buy signal than not.
 More precisely, every indicators generates a buy signal between 67 % and
 73% of the time.
 We can observe that the indicators are highly correlated, with minimum
 correlation between two indicators being 
\begin_inset Formula $0.44$
\end_inset

, and the minimum correlation between two indicators of the same class (moving
 average, momentum, volume) being 
\begin_inset Formula $0.64.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Methodology of testing predictability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section describes the way of testing the out-of-sample predictive performan
ce of a forecasting model compared to the benchmark historical average model.
 The methodology is also detailed by Wang
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Wang2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The starting point is the following univariate linear regression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r_{t+1}=\alpha+\beta x_{t}+\varepsilon_{t+1},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 is the aforementioned equity risk premium, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{t}$
\end_inset

 is a vector of predictive variables (consisting of zeros and ones in this
 case), and 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{t}$
\end_inset

 is an error-term assumed to be independent and identically distributed.
 Following the framework of Wang, I employ a recursive, expanding estimation
 window to generate out-of-sample forecasts.
 In particular, I divide the whole sample of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 observations of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{t}$
\end_inset

 into an in-sample part containing the first 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 (in this study, 
\begin_inset Formula $M=180$
\end_inset

) observations, and an out-of-sample part containing the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $N=T-M$
\end_inset

 observations.
 The out-of sample forecast for some period 
\begin_inset Formula $K+1$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $K\geq M$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $K<T$
\end_inset

 is then given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{r}_{K+1}=\hat{\alpha}_{K}+\hat{\beta}_{K}x_{K},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\alpha}_{K}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\beta}{}_{K}$
\end_inset

 are OLS-estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 These estimates are obtained by regressing 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ r_{t}\right\} _{t=2}^{K}$
\end_inset

 on a constant and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ x_{t}\right\} _{t=1}^{K-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Throughout this process, a series of N out-of-sample forecasts are generated.
 We compare these predictions to the benchmark model by using out-of-sample
 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the defined as the percentage reduction in mean squared forecast
 error of the model of interest relative to the benchmark model, thus theoretica
lly, it can obtain a negative value.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{OOS}^{2}$
\end_inset

 results are reported in Table2.
 We can observe that the 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{OOS}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is positive for all of the indicators, suggesting the predictability of
 stock returns, although a test of the significance of the difference between
 the models of interest and the benchmark model is not carried out.
\end_layout

