\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $R_{OOS}^{2}$
\end_inset

is positive for all variables, which implies stock return predictability
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Testing the momentum of predictability
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Wang
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Wang2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 defines momentum of predictability as the property whereby predictability
 present during a past period is also found in the current period.
 In other words, we can say that momentum of predictability is present in
 a model, if it is more likely to outperform the benchmark model in the
 current period, given that it did so in the recent past.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Current and past predictability is defined based on the squared error of
 the predictions.
 Current predictability is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cp=\left(\left(r_{t}-\hat{r}_{t}\right)^{2}<\left(r_{t}-\bar{r}_{t}\right)^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

a logical function, which thus takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $1,$
\end_inset

if the condition in the parenthesis is satisfied and -1 otherwise.
 Similarly, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
pp\left(k\right)=\left(\stackrel[j=t-k]{t-1}{\sum}\left(r_{t}-\hat{r}_{t}\right)^{2}<\stackrel[j=t-k]{t-1}{\sum}\left(r_{t}-\dot{r}_{t}\right)^{2}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is the lookback period.
 
\begin_inset Formula $pp\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 takes the value 1, when the model of interest produced a smaller sum of
 squared error than the benchmark model throughout the past k months., and
 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 I considered lookback periods of 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,3,6,9,12.$
\end_inset

 I test the momentum of predictability under the null hypothesis that 
\begin_inset Formula $pp\left(k\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $cp_{t}$
\end_inset

 are serially independent.
 For this purpose, I use the Pesaran-Timmermann statistic for directional
 accuracy testing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since I found the aforementioned test to be rather inadequately documented,
 I shortly include its methodology.
 The test examines whether the sign of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-element vector 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 does a significantly better job than a random forecast in oredicting the
 sign of an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-element vector 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, First, we define the vectors
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{x}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mathrm{\begin{array}{cc}
where & x>0\end{array}}\\
0 & \begin{array}{cc}
\mathrm{where} & \mathrm{x\leq0}\end{array},
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{y}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mathrm{\begin{array}{cc}
where & y>0\end{array}}\\
0 & \begin{array}{cc}
\mathrm{where} & \mathrm{y\leq0}\end{array},
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{xy}=\begin{cases}
1 & \mathrm{\begin{array}{cc}
where & xy>0\end{array}}\\
0 & \begin{array}{cc}
\mathrm{where} & \mathrm{xy\leq0},\end{array}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $xy$
\end_inset

 is the vector which is the elementwise product of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 For each of these three vectors, let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{x},p_{y}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{xy}$
\end_inset

be the proportion of ones in 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{x},d_{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{xy}$
\end_inset

 respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{i}=\frac{p_{i}\left(1-p_{i}\right)}{n},
\]

\end_inset

for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=x,y,xy.$
\end_inset

 Now 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{*}=p_{x}p_{y}+\left(1-p_{x}\right)\left(1-p_{y}\right),
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{xy}^{VAR}=\frac{p_{*}\left(1-p_{*}\right)}{n},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{*}^{VAR}=\left(2p_{y}-1\right)^{2}q_{x}+\left(2p_{x}-1\right)^{2}q_{y}+4q_{x}q_{y},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{*}$
\end_inset

 can be interpreted as the expected proportion of correct guesses of sign
 change assuming serial independence.
 The test statistic is given by the formula 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
PT=\frac{p_{xy}-p_{*}}{\sqrt{p_{xy}^{VAR}-p_{*}^{VAR}}},
\]

\end_inset

which follows a standard normal distribution under the null hypothesis.
 The test results with the p-values are reported in Table3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

