</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Results of testing the MoP.
 The p-values are much higher than in Wang's similar table, indicating there
 is no significant MoP for technical indicators
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I find that 8 of the employed 14 variables has no significant momentum of
 predictability for any lookback period.
 The moving average based indicators MA(1,9), MA(1,12), MA(2,12), the momentum-b
ased MOM(9) and the volume-based VOL(1,9) and VOL(2,9) show somewhat significant
 momentum of predictability (on a significance level of 5%) with one of
 the longer lookback periods (
\begin_inset Formula $k=\mathrm{6,9}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

), which.
 Moreover, none of the 70 p-values of Table3 is less than 1 percent, which
 suggests that there is no momentum of predictability for these 14 technical
 indicators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To more formally conclude that there is no signficant momentum of predictability
 present, I used False Discovery Rate controlling (by Benjamini Hochberg
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Benjamini1995"
literal "false"

\end_inset

), more precisely the Benjamini–Hochberg–Yekutieli procedure.
 In this test, we rearrange the computed 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 p-values in ascending order: 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\left(1\right)}\leq P_{\left(2\right)}\leq\ldots\leq P_{\left(n\right)}$
\end_inset

, and look for the largest 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{\left(k\right)}\leq\frac{k}{n\cdot c\left(n\right)}q^{*},$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}$
\end_inset

is the control parameter, the expected proportion of false discoveries,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c\left(n\right)=1$
\end_inset

, since the tests in this case are positively correlated.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{*}=5\%$
\end_inset

, the test yields that none of the discoveries are true positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
MoP of different groups of technical indicators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the previous section, I tested 14 technical indicators, and concluded
 that they do not exhibit any significant momentum of predictability.
 Some papers, on the other hand, use a higher number of technical variables
 to examine their performance (e.
 g.
 Okunev
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Okunev2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, using 354 moving average rules on the foreign exchange market)-
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since different classes (moving-average, momentum, volume-based) of technical
 strategies tend to give more homogenous signals, I also analyse the performance
 of the average MA-based, momentum-based, and volume based strategies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, following Okunev
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand keyonly
key "Okunev2003"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, I compute monthly signals for 354 moving-average based strategies with
 
\begin_inset Formula $s=1,2,...,12$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $l=2,3,...,36$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $s<l$
\end_inset

, meaning
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{MA}_{t}^{\mathrm{AVG}}=\frac{\stackrel[s=1]{12}{\sum}\stackrel[l=s+1]{36}{\sum}I\left(\mathrm{MA}_{\mathit{s,t}}\geq\mathrm{MA}_{\mathit{l,t}}\right)}{354},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is the indicator function which takes the value 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 is the condition in the parenthesis is satisfied and 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 otherwise.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Secondly, the average signal given by momentum based strategies is computed
 using MOM(
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

) for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1,2,...,36$
\end_inset

: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{MOM_{\mathit{t}}^{AVG}}=\stackrel[m=1]{36}{\sum}I\left(P_{\mathit{t}}\geq P_{\mathit{t-m}}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lastly, the average of the volume-based strategies is computed for the same
 short and long moving-averages as for simple MA-based strategies, meaning
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathrm{VOL}_{t}^{\mathrm{AVG}}=\frac{\stackrel[s=1]{12}{\sum}\stackrel[l=s+1]{36}{\sum}I\left(\mathrm{MA_{\mathit{s,t}}^{OBV}}\geq\mathrm{MA_{\mathit{l,t}}^{OBV}}\right)}{354}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, since all of them trying to extract the trend from price movements,
 technical indicators are highly correlated.
 Neely found that in the principal component analysis of the the14 technical
 indicators that paper employed, the first component explains over 70% of
 the variance.
 Considering this, I also analyse the momentum of predictability of the
 first principal component extracted from the PCA for the previously constructed
 744 strategies.
 This component, further denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{PC^{TECH}}$
\end_inset

still manages to explain more than 55% of the variance in spite of the magnitude
s larger number of variables.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After constructing these variables, I perform the same PT-test to test the
 momentum of predictability, the results of which are reported in Table3.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
wide false
sideways false
status open

